28. Concurrent editing safety: Optimistic locking + live polling [STATUS: COMPLETE]

Context:
The app has zero protection against concurrent edits. Two users editing the same
node results in silent last-write-wins data loss. The frontend only fetches tree
data after the local user's own mutations — there is no polling or push mechanism.
This blocks production deployment for teams.

This ticket adds two layers: (1) optimistic locking via version columns to prevent
silent overwrites, and (2) lightweight polling so users see each other's changes
within ~5 seconds.

Design Decisions:
- Two version counters: TreeRow.version (bumped on ANY tree mutation — used for
  polling) and NodeRow.version (bumped on node update — used for per-node conflict
  detection on the debounced auto-save).
- Version check is opt-in: NodeUpdate.version and TreeUpdate.version are optional.
  When None, no check is performed. This preserves backwards compatibility for CLI,
  chat agent, and existing API consumers.
- Only the frontend actively sends versions for conflict detection. The chat agent
  always reads latest state first, so last-write-wins is acceptable there.
- Polling uses a lightweight endpoint (GET /trees/{id}/version) returning a single
  integer, not the full tree payload.

Phase 1: Backend — Schema, Exception, Migration

  1a. Add version columns — schema.py
  - TreeRow: add version: Mapped[int] = mapped_column(Integer, default=1,
    nullable=False) after updated_at
  - NodeRow: add version: Mapped[int] = mapped_column(Integer, default=1,
    nullable=False) after updated_at (before the tree relationship)

  1b. Add VersionConflictError — exceptions.py
