29. User management: Authentication with login/password [STATUS: COMPLETE]
Depends on: Ticket 28

Context:
The app currently has no concept of users. All API endpoints are open. For team
collaboration, users need to identify themselves so changes can be attributed and
access can be controlled. This ticket adds a users table, registration, login, and
JWT-based authentication.

Design decisions:
- JWT tokens (not session cookies). Stateless, works when each user runs their own
  API server pointing at a shared PostgreSQL. No shared session store needed.
- Shared JWT_SECRET via .env (OST_JWT_SECRET). All API instances that share the
  same DB must use the same secret so tokens are valid across instances.
- Tokens expire after 7 days. Refresh is a simple re-login (no refresh token
  complexity).
- Registration is open (no invite flow). Any user with access to the API can
  register. This matches the lightweight deployment model (shared DB, local stacks).
- Password hashing via bcrypt (passlib or bcrypt library).
- Auth is opt-in at first: if no users exist in the DB, all endpoints remain open
  (graceful migration for existing single-user deployments). Once the first user
  registers, auth is enforced.
- display_name is the user-visible name (shown in attribution, presence, etc.).
  email is the login identifier.

Phase 1: Backend — Schema + Migration

  1a. UserRow — schema.py
  - id: String(36), primary key (UUID)
  - email: String(200), unique, non-nullable (login identifier)
